column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: At approximately 09:08 hours on January 4, 2013, the KCS mechanical department reported a strong ammonia odor coming from railcar UTLX950861 in Zone 5 Track 104 of the KCS Kansas City, MO Knoche Yard.  No injuries reported and emergency responders were activated. At approximately 10:15 the emergency responders arrived onsite and were briefed on situation.     Upon further inspection of tank car UTLX950861, it was determined a very small leak had formed on the Pressure Relief Valve (PRV) underneath the protective housing. The odor was light and not detectable at ground level by responder but was slightly detectable at the top of the car with the protective housing cover open. The responder renewed the PRV o-ring, correcting the release. The internal pressure of the tank car was okay at 40 psi and all closures (valves and plugs) were found tool tight.     File Note Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact  consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: Recommendations:    The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities,   and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence.     It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.    The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs. To improve communications the shipper can provide contact information in this web site (Contact Network) to better facilitate incident response and post incident communications as applicable.

column168: At approximately 5:45 AM on January 9, 2013, it was reported that a very strong odor was emanating from potentially 3 tank cars in the KCS Port Arthur yard in Port Arthur, TX. Emergency notifications were made and KCS responders were activated.     KCS responders arrived on-site, received situation briefing, and began root cause investigation on the first tank car, TELX90451. After a thorough inspection was performed including air monitoring, tool tightness and visual inspection of all tank car appurtenances, it was determined that tank car TELX90451 was not cause of odor. The KCS responders then proceeded to 2nd of 3 potential releasing tank cars. After thorough inspection of tank car TELX90455, including air monitoring, tool tightness and visual inspection of all tank car appurtenances, it was determined that tank car TELX90455 was not cause of odor. KCS responders proceeded to final tank car.    Upon further inspection of tank car TELX 539 by KCS responders, it was determined that the vapor line valve stem packing was loose and verified as the cause of trace vapor release. After information on tank car TELX 539 was disseminated, the car owner (Arkema) sent their own emergency responder to verify valve stem packing condition. Upon further inspection by shipper responder, it was determined that the vapor valve on tank car TELX 539 was one of the new valve types which are supposed to improve packing performance in changing temperatures. The packing was found at less than 20 inch pounds when the packing should have been tightened to 32 inch pounds to operate properly. The packing was properly tightened to the appropriate torque value thus correcting the release.     The Arkema responders double checked the other two tank car appurtenances for approriate tightness before departing from rail yard.    *No accidents of injuries were reported.    File Note Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact  consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.

column168: On 1 Jan 2013, at 0202 hrs, personnel in the CSXT Tilford yard discovered ASOX 299064, a loaded tank car of Styrene Monomer-Stabilized, leaking from the bottom of the car. The car was isolated and Chemtrec - Americas Styrenics, NRC, and GEPDEOC were notified, CHEMTREC report #2013-01-01-00005. SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a leaking bottom outlet valve packing nut. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Dawn Brubaker, 979-239-8113. Contractor personnel removed the skid plate, tightened the packing nut, decontaminated the car and cleaned up spilled material. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. A 7.1 report is required.    Cause Code: 547  NARRI:  5 (5+1+0) x (2+0)=60

column168: THE RELEASE WAS FROM ALOHA PETROLEUM PIPELINE LOCATED IN WEST OAHU BETWEEN THE ALOHA TERMINAL FACILITY AT 91-139 HANUA STREET, KAPOLEI HAWAII AND THE BARDERS POINT HARBOR. ALOHA PETROLEUM HIRED CATHODIC PROTECTION CONTRACTOR, CORRPRO COMPANY (2799 MILLER STREET, SAN LEANDRO, CALIFORNIA 94577, PHONE 510-614-8800), TO UPGRADE THE PIPELINE CATHODIC PROTECTION SYSTEM. CORRPRO SUBCONTRACTED PRECISION DRILLING SERVICES (373 WALOPUA PLACE, HONOLULU, HAWAII 96825, PHONE 808-282-2055) TO DRILL TEN WELLS (6 INCH WELL X 10 FEET DEEP) TO INSTALL THE NEW ANODES. AT 10:00AM WHILE DRILLING 5TH HOLE, THE DRILL RIG HIT THE PIPELINE CAUSING THE RELEASE. TOMMY YAMAMOTO, AN ALOHA PETROLEUM TFM TERMINAL FACILITY EMPLOYEE WHO WAS AT THE RELEASE SITE DURING THE DRILLING OPERATION IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE CONTROL ROOM AT CHEVRON WHO WAS USING THE PIPELINE TO TRANSFER NAPHTHA TO THE PIER, TO STOP PUMPING. CHEVRON STOPPED PUMPING WITHIN MOMENTS. TOMMY NOTIFIED WAYNE CONDIT, GENERAL MANAGER, TERMINALS AND TRANSPORTATION FOR ALOHA PETROLEUM THAT THE DRILL RIG HIT OUR PIPELINE AND A RELEASE OF ABOUT 15 TO 20 GALLONS OCCURRED. THE RELEASE WAS ABSORBED INTO THE SOIL IMMEDIATELY SURROUNDING THE 6 INCH WELL. THERE ARE NO STORM DRAINS IN THE AREA AND THE RELEASE DID NOT MIGRATE OFF SITE.
column169: ALOHA PETROLEUM WILL REPAIR THEPIPE WITH TYPE "B" SLEEVE AND A PIPELINE WRAP SYSTEM. THE PIPELINE WRAP SYSTEM IS DOT-OPS APPROVED AND PROTECTS THE LINE UP TO 700 PSI. column168: Load was booked non-hazardous.  No later communication was received that there would be hazardous materials on board.  JBH driver, who has applied for but not yet received a hazardous materials endorsement, was dispatched on the load.  While at the receiver, driver was handed hazmat placards and bill of lading.  Driver called management, attempting to confirm wither or not this was a hazmat load and was told the load "is not supposed to be."  Driver proceeded to transport vehicle to an intermodal rail facility where the load in-gated and proceeded by train.  Because the load was not flagged as a hazmat load, the railroad was not informed there was hazmat present on the load, nor did they receive a copy of the hazmat BOL.  The mistake was noted when the vehicle out-gated at it's destination by a subsequent driver and reported to JBHT Compliance.
column169: Load notes have been added reminding drivers to always check their bills for any amount of hazmat.  This example will be incorporated in orientation and quarterly safety training as a reminder of how inattentiveness can lead to transportation of undeclared hazardous materials.  Marketing will be reminded of the crucial importance of marking hazmat loads in our load system in order to better ensure proper compliance.  JBHT accepts all responsibility here; as an FYI, the shipper has been reminded that they too have a responsibility to help ensure that vehicles are legal prior to leaving their property.

column168: Tank car UTLX 48327 at the railyards repair track for wheel inspection due to a previous wayside detector alarm was reported dripping commodity from its bottom outlet valve (BOV) area onto the frozen snow packed ground.  A catch receptacle and absorbent pads were placed under UTLX 48327. Inspection revealed the BOV's operating handle was not properly pinned in the closed position. Responders moved and pinned the BOV's operating handle in the closed position and tool tightened the BOV's valve stem packing gland nut which ended the commodity drips. Captured spillage was earmarked for appropriate disposal along with impacted snow and top ballast that was collected. Microbial solution was applied to the area to treat any residual spillage remnants.

column168: Tank car UTLX 650469 in the railyard was reported emanating a commodity odor. Immediate inspection by BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders revealed the odor source was at the manway closure of UTLX 650469. No liquid release was evident.  All eight manway securement bolts were found tool tight and the shipper seal numbered 112946 was intact at the manway closure. Inspection of the manway gasket condition found the gasket torn and deteriorated, thus not providing a good closure seal. A new manway gasket was installed and the manway lid was resecured, which ended any further escape of commodity vapors/odor. Seal BNSF 06157776 was applied at the manway closure. Response was concluded by 1430 hrs. PST, 01/05/2013.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A 'sulfur' odor was reported emanating from the railyard's repair track area. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders inspected the railcars at the repair track and determined tank car UTLX 672867 was the odor source. Previous hardened sulfur spillage was noted around the manway nozzle but no free flowing liquid was observed. The responders reported finding 4 of 8 manway securement swing bolt nuts less that tool tight. The manway gasket was inspected and found to be serviceable, thus the loose manway securement nuts prevented a good closure seal and allowed commodity odor/vapors to escape. The manway lid was closed and all manway securement swing bolt nuts were properly tool tightened. After the manway was secured, no further commodity odor was detectable.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

Trailer was picked up on 1/09/2013 @ 1600 hrs @ origin and arrived at destination on 01/09/2013 @ 2300.  Driver parked at destination's designated parking area and went into the sleeper.  At approx. 0200 the desination's security guard noticed flames coming from the trailer and woke up the driver.  The driver immediately un hooked the trailer and moved the tractor to a safe place.  Rineco's Emergency Response was notified and a 3rd party emergency responder arrived on the site within 1 hour. Local responders on the scene were the local fire department, LADEQ, Facility receiving personnel.  Rineco's ER coordinatorin-consult with persons on scene to direct response. material was not realeased on to the ground and water was not used.  Sand was used to extinguish the fire and the material was off-loaded from original transport.  Reponse at that point was closed.  The heat from the fire caused the trailer to melt and buckle resulting in a few holes down each side of the trailer making the trailer's structural integrity a total loss.
column169: All procedures were followed by transporter.  The transport vehicle contained all burned material and the rapid response prevented any material release to the ground.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: A shipment of hazardous waste was picked up and brought back to the intermediate truck transfer facility for consolidation on another trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility.  Upon backing into the dock, a drum tipped over in the trailer, spilling approximately 10 gallons through a slit in the bung.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and contained the spilled material with a suitable absorbent material.  The drum was overpacked into a salvage drum along with the material used to clean up the spill.  The trailer was cleaned with a cleaning compound.  The shipment was loaded onto the trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The driver did not check the drum carefully--the bung was damaged when picked up.  He also did not properly block and brace the shipment and when the trailer backed into the dock and hit the dock bumpers, the drum fell over.  The driver was suspended for 1 day without pay and proper container selection and blocking and bracing will be reviewed with him upon his return.

column168: A shipment of hazardous waste arrived at the intermediate truck transfer facility and was unloaded onto the dock.  During a routine dock check on the second morning, a small amount of liquid was noticed on the dock floor.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the spill.  The inner liner had split under the weight of the sludge material in the boxes.  The shipment was overpacked into drums as it was felt it would not withstand the rigors of transportation to the intended waste disposal site.  The incident was reported to the Nebraska DEQ, incident number 171

Driver was traveling East bound on I-90 topped a hill and curve, saw two trucks off the side of the road one on the left and one on the right, he steered between them and tried to stop but a third truck and trailer was jack knifed totally blocking the road way, he steered a as best he could away from the cab but hit the trailer near the rear axle and slid off the roadway.He call 911 and reported the accident and the haz-mat load. On January 17, 2013, at 2005 hours, a Trainmaster at the CSXT Willard Terminal, Willard, Ohio noticed an excessive amount of venting and condensate coming from the valve compartment of LTCX 1902, a loaded tank car of UN1951, Argon. The tank car was isolated. The shipper, Praxair Inc., was notified via Chemtrec, report #2013-0117-00252 . The shipper representative, John Gulotta, 630-450-0308 was notified of the situation and responded a technician to meet our Terminal employees and attempt repairs. At 0240 the on site technician determined he was unable to secure the release of vapors which was determined to be from the bonnet nut on the three inch liquid line. Praxair sent two additional technicians in an effort to attempt repairs and tighten the bonnet nut with a specialized wrench. CSXT dispatched SPSI, a CSXT emergency response contractor, to the Willard Terminal in an effort to assist if needed and ensure safety to employees in the Terminal. The vapor release was secured by tightening the bonnet nut thus stopping the vapor release and LTCX 1902 was released for disposition.   This incident did require a special move.    NARRI: 5(5+1+0)x(2+0) = 60  Cause code:716

column168: A shipment of five 5 gallon gerry cans and steel iron was received in good condition from the shipper at our wharehouse location.   An hour after receipt, a company employee was handling the iron, at which point he poked one of the 5 gallon containers of battery acid, puncturing a small hole in it.   The five 5-gallon gerry cans were shrink wrapped together, and our employee did not know at that time that he put a small hole in through the plastic.   The shipment was placed aside for 3 to 4 hours at which point it was being retrieved for transporation, and at this time discovered that it was leaking.   The singel container was placed on its side, stopping further leaking, and baking soda was applied to the areas where it leaked onto.   The customer/shipper was notified.  The remaining amount of acid in the damaged container is slavaged into another new container.   Areas have been cleaned up.  No harmful exposures identified.  Employees used PPE while mitigating clean up.
column169: This was a employee, human error in handling long metal steel stock.   The employee has been notified and further awarness training provided to watch out for long metal ends, to keep from poking other freight.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: At 01:47 on 01/17/2013, a strong odor was reported to be coming from tank car GATX201448 in the Beamont Yard in Beaumont, TX. Appropriate notificaitons were made and emergency responders were activated. The car was isolated in zone 2 on track 806 in the Beaumont Yard.    Upon arrival, the emergency responder noted no odor was detected nor unsafe air monitoring readings. Upon further inspection of the tank car, the responder noted a "very very small leak" was coming from the pressure relief device (PRD) and "did not present a hazardous situation." The first emergency responder did not have necessary equipment required to make the appropriate repairs to the PRD so a second responder was activated.     Once the second emergency responder arrived, they replaced 2 O-rings in the PRD and the leak was stopped. Both O-rings were deformed in a flattened fashion. The car only had 10 psi pressure however the defective O-rings, coupled with the unusually cold temperatures, caused the PRD to seep very slightly. The responders secured the tank car and then performed a safety brief everyone at the yard office before departing the property.    *No injuried were reported    File Note Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact  consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: Recommendations:    The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities,   and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable.    For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence   of unsafe transportation conditions.    The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs. To improve communications the shipper can provide contact information in this web site (Contact Network) to better facilitate incident response and post incident communications as applicable.

Hepaco, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the bottom outlet valve handle was pinned and sealed in the open position and the bottom outlet valve cap was less than tool tight. column169: Transfer procedure will make connection of vapor recovery mandatory on all fuel drops.  Currently, vapor recovery required in only certain counties.  Had vapor recovery hose been in place, product would not have been released.

The driver reported that when he was loading the cargo tank at the well site, he forgot to open the internal valve on the cargo tank.  When the pressure built up from the closed valve, it blew the seal and released about 10 gallons of oil before they could shut down.   A vac truck was used to clean up the spill.
column169: The driver takes full responsibility for allowing himself to be distracted and not following proper procedure.  He will not allow that to happen in the future.

column168: Product was being pumped from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank for about 5 minutes when a small leak developed on a section of hose between the pump and customer tank.  A small amount of material hit the back of the driver's pant leg before the pump could be stopped. driver immediately got a water hose to rinse down his leg, then showered and put on different clothes.  He went to a clinic to be checked out just as a precaution.  He was given some cream to put on the back of his leg and was released back to work. Spill went into a containment area and customer handled the clean up.
column169: The driver should have been using his hose instead of the customer hose for the unload.  He also was not wearing the required PPE.  If he had his chemical suit on as his work assignment indicated, material would not have penetrated his pant leg.  The customer will refuse future loads unless all requirements are met.

column168: Driver had been using air pressure to transfer the material from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank for about 5 minutes when the plant operator came out of the building and told the driver to slow down the transfer.  Liquid/foam was coming out of the top of the tank.  driver then opened the discharge valve just a little on the cargo tank and completed the delivery without further incident.  The foamover went in a containment area and the customer handled the cleanup according to company procedures.
column169: When we haul this product in the future, the driver will now see a note in his work assignment stating that the product foams and he should open the discharge valve just a little and go slow with the transfer.

column168: QUEST LINER HAD TWO LIQUID BULK TRAILERS LOADING ETHYL ALCOHOL (DENATURED) ON 1/4/13 IN MUSCATINE IOWA. THESE TWO TRAILERS WERE STAGED AT THE QUEST LINE BLUE GRASS TERMINAL AROUND 1600 ON 1/4. ON 1/5 AT 1615 QUEST LINER RECEIVED A CALL FROM ONE OF ITS DRIVERS THAT ONE OF THE TRAILERS WAS EMPTY. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION BY QUEST LINER, BLUE GRASS POLICE AND SCOTT COUNTY SHERIFF IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A SECOND TRAILER HAD BEEN TAMPERED WITH AS WELL. OUR INITIAL THOUGHT WAS THEFT AS WE COULD NOT SMELL OR SEE ANY ALCOHOL NEAR THE TRAILERS. ON MONDAY 1/7, WHILE VISITING OUR NEIGHBOR, RICH METALS, WE REALIZED THAT 14,100 GALLONS OF ALCOHOL FLOWED ONTO THEIR (RICH METALS) PROPERTY. THIS WAS AN ACT OF VANDALISM AS THESE TRAILERS WERE SEALED WITH TAMPER EVIDENT CABLE SEALS. FOUR SEALS WERE CUT TO GAIN ENTRY TO THE INTERNAL AND EXTERNAL VALVES, ALLOWING THE PRODUCT TO FLOW FROM THE TRAILER. THE CUT SEALS WERE FOUND LYING ON THE GROUND. INVESTIGATION IS ONGOING BY THE AUTHORITIES. PREMIUM ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED AND ASSESSED THE SITE. THE STANDING ALCOHOL WAS ABSORBED AND SOIL SAMPLES TAKEN. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT EXCAVATION OF THE SOIL WAS NEEDED. CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED AND NEW SOIL WAS PUT IN ITS PLACE. CLEANUP IS COMPLETED.    *CONTINUED INFO FROM PART II AND PART III* LOAD/TRAILER #2  PART II  13. DESTINATION 2909 HIGHLAND AVE CINCINNATI OH SHIPPING #1065930  PART III  28. column168: Loving County - The driver of a semitrailer truck escaped serious injury early this New Year's Day (01JAN2013)morning after his truck hit several cattle on FM 652 about fifteen miles east of Orla, TX.  Edward H. Birdwell was traveling southwest on FM652 early New Year's Day when his truck struck several cows which had wandered onto the roadway.  After the impact, Birdwell's truck spun into the south shoulder and flipped over, said the Department of Public Safety officers that investigated the crash.  Birdwell is an employee of Plains Marketing, L. P. working out of their Hobbs, NM Truck District.  Birdwell was taken to the Reeves County Hospital by Pecos Ambulance Service.  He was examined and evaluated there and subsequently transported by helicopter to University Medical Center in El Paso, TX.  The cattle did not survive the impact. Five adult cows and two calves were killed.  Authorities speculate the cows escaped through a gap in a fence and poorly maintained cattle guards.  The semitrailer and its crude oil payload were a total loss.  The owner of the cows and adjacent landowners were contacted. The Texas Department of Transportation (TxDOT) removed the dead animals.  The cargo tank rupture allowed crude oil to leak onto an area of pasture south of the FM652 Right-of-Way where the semitrailer came to rest. Plains' Hobbs Emergency Response Team contained the spill using containment booms, absorbents, and soil. Duration of the spill was approximately one hour. The cargo tank rupture was a circular breach in the lower driver side quadrant of the tank shell, approximately 10' rearward of the front bulkhead; approximately 3" in diameter.
column169: Plains Marketing, L. P. intends to increase driver training on situational awareness and increased attention to potential hazards of driving in darkness, and the special hazards night driving presents.  Additionally, Plains Marketing, L. P. will include orientation and training for its drivers on the Texas Open Range laws, with specific emphasis on the counties in which Plains operates. Loving County is "Open Range" and this incident will be used as a case study to illustrate the additional dangers that drivers in Open Range locations may encounter.    Plains will also consider "Deer Whistles", devices mounted on the fronts of cars, trucks, and motorcycles, which allegedly produce ultrasonic frequencies and/or audible sounds from the wind rushing through them. These sounds are supposed to repel or warn animals, particularly deer, elk, moose,dogs, and cattle of oncoming vehicles.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Too Much Weight on Package
column168: A BNSF mechanical inspection in the railyard of an inbound BNSF intermodal train revealed intermodal trailer FSTZ 882497 leaking an unknown liquid substance onto the entrained intermodal flatcar's decking that FSTZ 882497 was riding upon. The intermodal flatcar with FSTZ 882497 was set-out from the train for further inspection. Interior inspection of FSTZ 882497 by contract responders revealed lading within FSTZ 882497 had shifted and some lading toppled due to insufficient blocking and bracing, thus longitudinal lading movement was not prevented. One palletized load fell onto the top of a poly tote which caused the commodity within the tote to seep out from the tote's top fill hole closure cap. The fill hole closure cap was resecured to a tighter position. All spillage was absorbed and cleaned. The lading within FSTZ 882497 was adjusted with hazardous material ladened totes repositioned to be less vulnerable from any load shift impacts.
column169: Ensure shipper's LTL shipments are properly blocked and braced to deter intransit longitudinal and lateral lading shifts.

column168: At 07:30 hours on 1/20/13 it was discovered that UTLX 209833 was leaking from a defective pressure relief device (PRV) in the Heavener Yard in Heavener, OK. Appropriate notifications were made and the tank car was taken out of active transport and isolated.    Upon further inspection by KCS personnel it was determined that the (PRV) was defective. The PRV had a broken shaft and both the spring and retainer were found to be inside the car already. The shipper transloaded the lading on 2/6/2013. The shipper will arrange for car to go to home shop to receive repairs. The shipper will arrange is responsible for the One Time Movement Approval, OTMA.    * No injuries reported    File Note Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact  consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: Recommendations:    The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities,   and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable.    For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence   of unsafe transportation conditions.    The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs. To improve communications the shipper can provide contact information in this web site (Contact Network) to better facilitate incident response and post incident communications as applicable.

column168: At approximately 22:00 hrs, tank car UTLX 201019 was found leaking from the top of the car during switching operations in the KCS Laredo Yard in Laredo, TX. Appropriate notifications were made and local emergency responders were activated. *No injuries were reported.    Upon arrival/inspection by responder, it was noted that 3 manway bolts were loose atop the tank car. column168: Driver was unloading #2 Diesel. Diesel began to bubble up at relief valve for UST at fill point. Driver shot off fuel flow from delivery tank. Driver pulled spill kit immediately with absorbent snakes and rags and was able to contain spill point. Grabbed shovel and pushed up snow to separate contaminated and uncontaminated snow and built a dam. Contractor (John Muggli Contracting) was called to come out and clean up. Driver and store manager assisted by putting down floor dry on the spill area which was on concrete at a retail gas station location. Floor dry laid down twice and swept after contractor clean up contaminated area.   Duration of spill was only a couple of minutes at a bubbling up pace until pressure equalized. Montana DEQ investigating site per follow-up conversation to determine point of malfunction as reading were taken ahead of time.     SERC (Montana DEQ) called (Katy Erny 406-841-5044 incident number not given as it was night watchman but gave facility ID of 908212). NRC contacted (PO2 Layman, incident number 1035704)
column169: Montana DEQ currently investigating cause of UST tank or gauge malfunction. Drivers sticking tanks before and after and tank chart available now to confirm fill.

column168: TAMPA, FL- TRANSFLO  Date of Release: 1/9/2013  Material Release Description: Propane  Quantity of Release: Estimated 2,341 lbs  Cause of Release: On 09 Jan 2013 at approximately 1650, A TRANSFLO transloading employee ascended railcar #GATX 75297 for gauging purposes. The transloader opened the dome lid and found propane leaking from the pressure relief valve. The Terminal Manager & Regional Operational Manager for Kinder Morgan (terminal operator)were immediately notified. They assessed the release and immediately called for evacuation of the terminal employees and called 911. Tampa Fire Dept (TFD), Emergency Response Team & HAZMAT teams responded. TRANSFLO (terminal owner), CSX Hazmat were also notified.  Water was applied by TFD which minimized the leak but it did not completely stop the release. At 1830 SWS Environmental Services arrived, assessed the situation, and applied hot water which stopped the leak. SWS environmental remained on site throughout the night to document railcar pressure readings. Pressure steadily dropped throughout the night from 279 psi at 2300hrs to 255 psi at 0700hrs 10Jan13. First offload of propane occurred at 0700hrs on 10Jan13 which dropped the railcar pressure to 170 psi. Remaining propane was offloaded in 3 additional railcar to truck transfers. Residue railcar remains on-site at the Tampa TRANSFLO Terminal waiting for a One-Time Movement Approval from the FRA to move the railcar to the repair shop.     ADDITIONAL INFORMATION:   1.Railcar was loaded in Illinois on 13Dec12; Recorded outage of 16”, Temp 46 degrees.  2.Railcar arrived Tampa TRANSFLO terminal 27Dec12; Recorded outage of 12”. Temperature 78 degrees.  3.No product was taken from nor added to this railcar since arrival at the TAMPA TRANSFLO Terminal.  4.Product does expand based on ambient temperature.  5.Temperature on 09 Jan13 in Tampa was 84 degrees (F).  6.Pressure Release Valve (PRV) is set at 280.5 psi  7.At load port the Railcar was BOL’ed with 134,001 lbs of product.  8.10 Jan13 – Railcar was emptied with the following lbs per load:  o       1st load – 36,360 lbs.  o 2nd load – 36,260 lbs.  o 3rd load – 39,280 lbs.  o 4th load – 19,760 lbs.  o Total – 131,660 lbs.  o Loss – 2,341 lbs  9.Vapor recovery operation: (From r/c GATX 75297 to TILX 3005958)  • GATX 75297 starting PSI 165lbs  • TILX 3005958: PSI 145lbs  Outage 14.5” Temp 71 degrees  • V/R stopped with PSI @ 185lbs, Outage 5”, temp 85 degrees on r/c TILX 3005958  10.Vapor recovery operation: (From r/c GATX 75297 to PLMX 135034)  • GATX 75297 starting PSI 50lbs  • PLMX 135034: PSI 125lbs Outage 11.5” Temp 72 degrees  • V/R completed: GATX PSI 20lbs  • PLMX 135034: PSI 140lbs Outage 8.0” Temp 76 degrees
column169: ROOT CAUSE: Unknown at this time. Root cause will not known until railcar can be inspected at the railcar repair facility.     CORRECTIVE ACTIONS:  Work with TRANSFLO to ensure shipper (NGL Supply) submits a request for an One-Time Movment Approval (OTMA) and is granted approval to move the residue railcar from the terminal to the railcar repair shop for inspection and repair.

column168: SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF ONE PALLET THAT HAD 9 SMALL DRUMS ON IT. ONE OF THE 9 DRUMS CAME FREE FROM THE PALLET. THIS DRUM THEN BEGAN TO LEAK ITS CONTENTS. AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT, THIS WAS THE ONLY ITEM ON THE TRAILER. THIS ONE DRUM CONTAINED APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS IN IT.  WHEN THE DRIVER DISCOVERED THE LEAK, HE IMMEDIATELY PULLED OVER AND PARKED HIS TRUCK. HE NOTIFIED HIS TERMINAL MANAGER IMMEDIATELY, AND HE IN TURN NOTIFIED HIS SAFETY DEPARTMENT.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE SCENE, AND STAYED AT THE SCENE UNTIL A HAZ-MAT TEAM ARRIVED. THE HAZ-MAT TEAM CONTAINED AND CLEANED THE SPILL, AND DISPOSED OF THE LEAKING CONTAINER.
column169: THE PRIMARY FAILURE ON THE DRIVER WAS TO PROPERLY BLOCK AND BRACE THIS LAST SHIPMENT ON THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER WAS RE-TRAINED ON THESE FUNDAMENTALS THE DAY FOLLOWING THIS INCIDENT. THIS TRAINING WAS CONDUCTED BY A MEMBER OF THE LOCAL FACILITIES SAFETY TEAM. THE RE-TRAINING HAS BEEN DOCUMENTED.

column168: Tank car TILX 192700 was reported dripping commodity from its bottom outlet valve (BOV) in the railyard. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders inspected TILX 192700 finding the BOV operating handle not in the fully closed position and commodity dripping from the BOV's valve stem. The responders repositioned the BOV operating handle to its closed position and tightened the packing gland nut at the BOV's valve stem, thus ending any further commodity drips. All spillage was evaporating. Afterwards, TILX 192700 was moved to the repair tracks where adjustments were made to the BOV operating handle to enable the operating handle to be securely pinned in the fully closed position.

column168: Tank car CPDX 110048 was reported emanating a commodity odor in the railyard. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders inspected CPDX 110048 and reported the odor source was at the 280.5 psi pressure relief device (PRD). No liquid release was evident and no vapor hiss was audible. The responders replaced the PRD O-rings which eliminated the commodity odor. The removed PRD O-rings appeared flat sided or within the compression set classification. The removed O-rings were forwarded to Carolina Seal Inc. for root cause failure analysis.

column168: Incident and root cause analysis:    At approximately 0600 on January 14th, 2013, the tires on our fiberglass tanker 24957 allegedly caught on fire en route from Henderson to Calvert City near mile marker 53 while traveling Southbound on the Pennyrile Parkway.  All eight tires on the rear of the tanker were destroyed in the fire.  Moreover, the fire and heat did extensive damage to the outer shell of the Fiberglass tanker that was reinforced with balsa wood.  The hose trays and transfer hoses were also burned up in the fire.  Consequently, the gasket inside the bottom belly valve assembly on the tanker failed because of the fire damage and allowed Hydrochloric Acid (32%) to start dripping out at the rear of tanker.    Based on our interviews with our two drivers on board and our inspection of the tanker after it was returned and dismantled in our fleet maintenance shop by our lead mechanic, it led us to suspect that we must have had a tire failure that started with the back right inside tire and then possibly caused the brake system to start dragging due to a gradual release of air pressure on our brake system.  After the tire caught fire, the situation continued to escalate until only the remnants of the steel cords and melted rubber remained on the rims.  Therefore, we could not confirm for sure what may have caused the tire failure.  Our drivers did not detect any tire problems when a pre-trip inspection was conducted.    Sequence of events leading up to the incident:    Our driver, Chris Reynolds, logged on duty at 0409 and proceeded to couple to Tanker 24957 loaded with Muriatic Acid (Hydrochloric Acid 32%).  Mack Tinsley, designated trainer and passenger, was assigned to ride with Chris on this delivery.  They conducted their Pre-Trip Inspection and did not detect any problems.  However, Chris explained that as he proceeded to make a turn, the trailer brakes suddenly locked up.  We had experienced a sudden drop in the ambient temperature overnight and it was below the freezing mark.  We suspected the issue was related to ice crystals in the air line due to moisture in the system.  Chris uncoupled from the tanker and contacted our Fleet Maintenance mechanic on duty.  The mechanic used our spot truck and added some airline drying fluid and got the trailer into our wash bay that is equipped with hot air drying equipment.  Our mechanic applied hot air to the back of the trailer and treated with the airline drying fluid to ensure the brakes were releasing properly.  After the tanker was released, Chris coupled to the tanker and then proceeded to our Guard House Scale without incident.  At approximately 5:30 a.m., they left the Henderson Facility and proceeded to the Pennyrile Parkway en route to Calvert City.    After traveling approximately 20 miles Southbound on the Pennyrile, they approached mile marker 54 (Calhoun exit) and noticed the truck was pulling hard while going up a hill.  After topping the hill, the truck was still pulling hard.  M
column169: Based on the sequence of events, we discussed the fact that when a combination unit appears to be pulling hard or losing power, we should not assume that it may be only engine related.  It may indeed be related to damaged tires and brake issues.  Therefore, if we are losing power, we should stop sooner and inspect the tires and brake system for any signs of damage or heat or anything else out of the ordinary.    During our investigation, we discussed possible causes such as the brakes out of adjustment, ice crystals in the airline due to moisture build up, brake hose failure, or brake valve failure.  Since the trailer tires never locked up we suspect a contributing factor related to something that created a gradual release of air pressure to the brake system that allowed the brakes to drag and not lock up.  It was very evident the right inside rear frame of the tanker showed signs of exposure to the greatest amount of heat.    This incident will be reviewed in our drivers safety meeting as a moment of high influence to ensure our operating procedures remain current and accurate and recurrent training requirements are conducted to support our hazmat training for general awareness, function specific, safety, and general security awareness and indepth security training of our site security plan for personnel security, physical security, and en route security.     Moreover, we will follow up with our emergency response team members to conduct a post-critique of our strengths and opportunities for improvement.

PAILS BAGS AND DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SCROUDED USING MTY PALLETS, PLYWOOD AND OR DUNNAGE. USING DECK BAGS OR LOAD LOCK BARS PROPERLY AND SAFELY TO LOAD FREIGHT ON TOP OF. RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS. RETRAIN IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN LOADING, SIGNAGES STATING, PAIL OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Tank car UTLX 211343 was reported leaking commodity from its top fitting area onto its side shell while in the railyard. Inspection by a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder and contract responders revealed the leak source was at the 165 psi pressure relief device (PRD). The commodity outage observed within UTLX 211343 was deemed appropriate, thus concluding that the PRD had failed. UTLX 211343 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard. Spillage on UTLX 211343 was cleaned. No further commodity release was observed as UTLX 211343 remained motionless. A like model replacement PRD was ordered, received and then installed on 2/05/2013 without further incident. The failed PRD incurred a broken stem at its bottom threaded area above the spring follower and retainer/locking nut area. The PRD spring and associated hardware could not be retrieved from inside UTLX 211343. A FRA OTMA to be requested by the shipper to move UTLX 211343 to the consignee for unloading with subsequent movement to a qualified repair facility for leakproofness testing.

column168: A 55 gallon drum was loaded with a bung inadequately tightened by shipper.  With motion incidental to transportation on intermodal rail, the bung came loose and leaked paint.   Most paint was contained within the intermodal unit; a small quantity leaked out through the floor of the unit and was contained in the rail yard's hazmat pit.  The spill was noted at the rail ramp with JBH driver arrived to power the intermodal container to its final stop.  Photos of the securement were up to AAR guidelines; no damage was noted to the packaging or evidence of load shift.  Photos revealed the discharge to have been caused by a leaking bung; the cause being inadequate tightening when shipped.
column169: Findings were forwarded to the shipper with a recommendation to be sure their drums are adequately sealed on future loads.

column168: According to the driver (Troy Mitchel) on scene, Troy arrived on location  at approximately 2300hrs and loaded on two locations. He stated that he was finished loading around 0030hrs then took a nap until 0245hrs. Troy mentioned that the conditions at the location (Antelope 3-5) where  cold and foggy. He stated that he left the location making a right turn and felt a small bump. Troy then  continued on the Jonah  Midcrest  Road approx. 1.5 miles until he approached highway  191 until he noticed  that his brakes  were locked  up on his pup trailer (1979  Polar Vin 4072). He stated that he then exited his truck and noticed that the pup was leaking natural gas condensate from a breach in the tank hull. He then contacted  Linn Energy  controller (Tyler) and notifed him of the accident. Troy also alleged  that he contacted another unkown Linn employee who told him that due to the time, date (holiday), and the fact that the spill would be reportable anyway  it would  be hard to find anyone to help. Troy stated that he waited  "hours"  for help but no one came to help and due to the "cold" he was unable to stay, so he unhooked the pup and left the scene  returning  to the shop in Lyman, Wy. It should be noted that Mr. Mitchel never did report this incident  to law enforcement or Feehan Trucking  as per Feehan Trucking policy.  At approx. 0430hrs Linn Energy contacted Ray Orana and I and notified  us of the incident. We arrived at the Jonah Midcrest Road at approx.  OBOOhrs and observed the afor mentioned  pup which was now off loaded by Partners  Trucking. I did observe that the pup had a tear along the right side approx. 5 ft long, under which the seam  of the tank had been seperated. We then responded to the Linn Enegry  Antelope 3-5 and observed where tracts left in the snow by Mitchel. He arrived on the location and loaded on the passenger side facing the oppisite  direction  than he had been trained. It should  be noted that Mitchel had another 15 to 20 feet of unused  area to perform a turn. Following the tire tracks the pup ran completely over a 4" steel pipe used  as a corner  post for the location berm  fence. The tire track continued out of the site after which the brakes  locked up due to the manifold and brake control valve being torn from the pup. The release of condensate was determined to be from 0300hrs until 0530hrs. It should  be noted that Mitchel's  statements were inconsistant and contradicted by Linn Energy  employees' statements.
column169: Feehan Trucking has implemented a remedial training concerning our safety and company  policies. We are also creating  an incident report protocol and call list with step by step instructions. Additionally, we will continue to review policies  and further safety programs to ensure  that Feehan Trucking is as safe as possible. A suggestion that I would  extend is that the Shipping Company (Linn Energy) would have emergency containment equipment (sand bags, containment tubs, oil cloths, eel.) on site in a location where  the Controllers would have access  to them  in case of such incidents. It should also be known  that Troy Mitchel was terminated from his position due to negligence and failure to perform manditory  duties outlined  in Feehan Trucking  Company Policies.

column168: Driver discovered smoke coming from trailer while parked at truck stop. Trailer door were opened and thick smoke but no flames were visible inside trailer. Local fire department was contacted and responded to scene. Hepaco was contracted to do remedial cleanup of water from fire department extinguishment of fire. It appeared that batteries within one of the pallets located nears center of trailer had short circuited and caused the batteries to overheat and packaging material to ignite. The amount of release is estimated. The cleanup done by contractor was mostly water used by fire department to extinguish the over heated batteries.    The incident occurred less than a mile form the shipper. The batteries were returned to the shipper

column168: DURING THE UNLOADING OF A CARGO TANK OF SULFUR DIOXIDE AT THE DESTINATION SITE, A MINOR LEAK WAS DETECTED BY THE DRIVER IN THE AREA OF HOSE CONNECTIONS TO THE CUSTOMER SYSTEM. THESE CONNECTIONS ARE LOCATED OUTSIDE THE SULFUR DIOXIDE STORAGE BUILDING ON AN EXTERIOR WALL. THE DRIVER TESTED THE CONNECTIONS FOR SULFUR DIOXIDE WITH AMMONIA SOLUTION AND CONFIRMED THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE CONNECTION AREA. HE PROCEEDED TO TIGHTEN THE KNOCK UNION THAT CONNECTS THE END OF THE UNLOADING HOSE TO THE CUSTOMER PIPING. AFTER TESTING THE CONNECTION AGAIN INDICATED SULFUR DIOXIDE IN THE AREA, HE EVACUATED THE HOSE AND DISCONNECTED THE HOSE TO APPLY PIPING COMPOUND AND RECONNECTED THE FITTINGS. BECAUSE OF INADEQUATE EVACUATION TIME, LIQUID HAD ENTERED THE HOSE AND A LEAK WAS STILL DETECTED. HE THEN ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE PACKING NUT ON THE HOSE VALVE. NOT HAVING THE PROPER SIZED WRENCH, WE LEFT TO RETRIEVE THE CORRECT SIZED WRENCH FROM THE TRUCK WHEN THE CUSTOMER PERSONNEL INFORMED HIM THAT AN EVACUATION WAS OCCURRING BECAUSE SULFUR DIOXIDE VAPOR HAD TRAVELED INSIDE THE BUILDING THROUGH AN OPEN DOOR AND SENSORS INSIDE THE BUILDING HAD ALARMED.
column169: REVIEWED CURRENT PROCEDURES AND PROVIDE ADDITIONAL DETAILS TO ASSURE LIQUID HAS NOT ENTERED THE UNLOADING HOSE BY ALLOWING ADDITIONAL VACUUM TIME. THE SEQUENCE OF CHECKS HAS BEEN DESIGNED TO REDUCE THE LIKELIHOOD OF LIQUID BEING IN THE HOSE AT ANY POINT OF THE PROCESS.    PROVIDE ADDITIONAL TRAINING FOR DRIVER AND CUSTOMER EMPLOYEES ON REVISED PROCEDURES.    REVIEW CURRENT PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT FOR DRIVER AND CO-DRIVER.    CUSTOMER WILL REDESIGN THE ENCLOSURE AROUND THE HOSE CONNECTION AREA TO ALLOW BETTER ASSESS TO MAKING SECURE KNOCK UNION CONNECTIONS.    CUSTOMER WILL REVIEW AND REVISE PROCEDURES TO ASSURE THE UNLOADING PERSONNEL ARE AWARE OF ANY CHANGES IN THE CONNECTION, UNLOADING AND TROUBLESHOOTING PROCESS.

column168: DRIVER WITH TRACTOR AND FLATBED TRAILER 5 x  550g IBC’s TRAVELING ON AN NARROW DIRT ROAD THOUGH  AN ORANGE GROVE THAT HAD DITCHES ON EITHER SIDE.  DRIVER CAME TOO CLOSE TO THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROAD WHERE LOOSE DIRT EXISITED.  THE SIDE OF THE ROAD GAVE WAY AND THE TRUCK ROLLED OVER INTO THE DITCH.  THE TRUCK WAS CARRYING SULFURIC ACID 50% IN IBC'S.  THE IBC'S DID NOT REUPTURE OR FAIL IN ANYWAY.  ANY SPILL THE OCCURED SEEPED OUT OF A VENT THAT INCORPORATED IN THE LIDS; THE COORSIVIE MATERIAL CORRODED THE INNER SPRINGS AND ALLOWED PRODUCT TO ESCAPE.  DURING INITAL RESPONSE, THE IBC’s WERE PUMPED OUT TO THE FULLEST EXTENT POSSIBLE.  THE TRUCK WAS LEFT OVERNIGHT TO AWAIT FOR HEAVY EQUIPMENT TO RAISE THE TRACTOR/TRAILER.  SLOW LEAKING OVERNIGHT RESULTED IN THE VOLUME SPILLED.  FROM THE KOWN AMOUNT ON BOARD AND THE RECOVERED MATERIAL, IT IS ESTIMATED THAT APRROXIMATELY 450 GALLONS SPILLS OUT OF THE CONTAINERS.  THE CONTAINERS WERE SHIPPED UNDERTHE DOT SP-12412 BUT THE RESULT OF THE SPILL WAS IN NO WAY A RESULT OF A FAILURE TO ADHERE TO SPECIFIED CONTROL MEASURES.
column169: ALL DRIVERS REVIEWED THE INCIDENT AND TRAINED ON THE HAZARDS OF NARROW ROADS, DANGERS OF DIRT ROAD WAYS AND DEFENSIVE TECHNIQUES WHILE DRIVING IN THIS TYPE OF ROAD CONDITION.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While making a delivery free product was discovered inside of the trailer. column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However, Wilson Trucking Corporation will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: A BNSF intermodal train pulling from a siding track onto the main track derailed the lead 13 rail cars. The cause of the derailment was attributed to a broken rail in the siding track. Intermodal flatcar with a 40 ft. intermodal container BMOU 472529 atop which was destined for export derailed on its side and came to rest in a depressed area with standing water. One end of BMOU 472529 was damaged and allowed 22 drums to roll out into the standing water. Many of the drums incurred sidewall dents/creases with some leaking from slits in those creased areas. Other drums were noted seeping product from their top closure seals/bungs. During removal of BMOU 472529 at the derailment site, 12 additional drums fell out from the damaged area of BMOU 472529. All loose damaged drums were placed on plastic sheeting awaiting placement into overpack drums. Berms were constructed to contain the standing water. Soil impact areas were excavated with soil placed in roll-off boxes. Soil and water sampling initiated for future remediation determination. Eventually all drums from BMOU 472529 were placed into overpack drums and properly labeled. The overpacked drums were loaded into two other intermodal containers and drayed to the BNSF Memphis intermodal facility for the shipper to survey and determine appropriate disposition.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: A 'gas' like odor was reported in the railyard near the area of the receiving tracks. BNSF mechanical /hazardous material responders investigating the odor source reported finding residue tank car GATX 3019 that previously arrived on an inbound BNSF train was the most likely source of the reported odor. Further inspection of GATX 3019 revealed vapor/odor emanating from the manway closure. The manway securement bolts were tight. The installed manway gasket was found cracked around its entire circumference at mid-width which contributed to the manway gasket not sealing properly. A new manway gasket was installed and the manway closure was properly resecured. Intact shipper seal B-102830 removed at the manway was replaced by seal BNSF 06157483. All other valves and fittings were inspected and found secure. Seal BNSF 06157482 was applied at the valve housing cover. No liquid commodity was released from GATX 3019. After securement was completed at 1355 hrs. PST, 1/31/2013, the odor around GATX 3019 dissipated.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: While making a bulk delivery at Mesa COnsolidated Water, driver overfilled the tank approx 200 gallons of 25% Caustic spilled in a secondary containment.     Tank level indicator was in a control room away from the tank. Before the bulk driver could stop pumping the product, approx 200 gals of product spilled into the secondary containment through a 4" overflow.  The customer was on his way to inform the driver to shut off delivery valve when the spill started to occur.  It seems like the customer ops personnel did not know the available capacity of the tank at the start of the delivery and mis-informed our driver about the available capacity of the tank.    Lack of knowledge of the tank capacity was the root cause of the incident.
column169: It is recommended that the tank capacity stocker be placed on the tank, so next time when the driver know that how much room is truly available in the tank based on the indicator reading.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Tank car UTLX 209876 was reported leaking commodity in the railyard. Inspection by BNSF mechanical personnel revealed the leak source was the 165 psi pressure relief device (PRD). The cause of the PRD failure appeared to be a broken valve stem. The PRD specification stampings indicated that it was manufactured in 2012 and per UTC it was installed on UTLX 209876 in June, 2012. No ground impact from spillage was observed and the spillage on UTLX 209876 was evaporating. UTLX 209876 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard awaiting lading transfer and application of a replacement PRD. No commodity release was observed while UTLX 209876 remained motionless. Commodity within UTLX 209876 was transferred into tank trucks without further incident on 2/15/2013. UTLX 209876 is awaiting installation of a replacement PRD and thence to a qualified repair facility under FRA OTMA FRA-13020113.

column168: Driver while attempting to position his truck to back up to a bulk fuel storage tank caught a pipe sticking out of the ground that pierced his fuel tank. He lost about 40 gals of clear diesel fuel over a 100 yard run. The ground was frozen and snow covered and he left a yellow line of diesel fuel in the snow. We contracted with West Central Environmental Consultants Rogers, MN office to clean up the spill on Monday. The scraped up the snow and removed it for disposal. This was the first time we tried to deliver to this customer.
column169: To prevent incidents like this in the future we are asking drivers if possible to go to new yards in daylight so they can see if they have debris or obstacles that could damage the truck.

column168: During the railcar unloading process, approximately 3600 gls of ethanol was released into containment when a butterfly-valve failed on an inbound railcar. After the KM Operator removed the seals and belly cap, product flowed freely as the valve holding the product was in the full open position (the handle however, indicated that it was closed). The KM Operator immediately notified management, and the Operations Supervisor was able to stem the flow of product by manipulating the handle back into the closed position after approximately 4 minutes of free flow. There were no injuries, and no product impacted the soil. As precautionary measures the surface of the loading rack was washed down with water to flush any residual product into containment. Covers were additionally placed on top of the containment sump to suppress potential flammable vapors. LEL monitors were used to determined the boundaries of the associated vapor hazard- the meters gave negative readings unless directly over the product. Calls were made to the local FD and Hazmat services to alert them of the situation and also ready their assets in the event the situation worsened. After the incident, UTLX was brought to the terminal to inspect the bottom outlet valve handle. It was learned that the pin connecting the handle and stem was missing (pin ensures that the handle is seated properly/secure).
column169: Kinder Morgan is currently testing various railcar emergency plugging devices to determine best management practices for stopping uncontrolled releases at the belly-valve. Upon completion/fabrication of the devices, terminals at KM will develop procedures for use and train their operations personnel on these devices as part of their worst case scenario training.

column162: REGIONAL SAFETY MANAGER SAFETY AND OPERATIONS
column168: Driver had stopped for fuel. After he left the fuel stop and was turning right to enter the freeway he saw in his mirror that a liquid trail was following him. He pulled over on the gravel shoulder of the entrance ramp to investigate. There was product spilling from the trailer from under the skin of the chemical trailer and he thought we had a tank failure andimmediately called his manager. The safety manager was immediatly called and Haz-MatOne (a Hazardous Material Responder) was called for immediate dispatch to the scene to get the product cleaned up. The trailer stopped leaking. We dispatched another unit to the scene to transfer the load onto a different trailer. During the transfer the drivers removed the seals to the manholes (front and back) which has the wash out caps in them to vent the trailer. The tank wash does the tank cleaning and seals the trailer. It was discovered that the employees at the tank-wash failed to place the caps on the wash out pipes in which released the product during transportation because of the surge and sloshing of the material in the trailer which resulted in the release of product spilling to the ground. The duration of the release was from the customer pick up site to the driver noticing the release and only when the product was surging and sloshing when starting or stopping.
column169: We have made contact to the shipper that the procedure to have the tank wash seal and secure the caps after tank is washed and not having anyone double-check that thecaps are replaced and tight is not an exceptable practice. From this day forward the tank wash will do what they have always done. The customer agrees and they will break the seals when the trailer is loaded and make sure the caps are in place and tight. They will then reseal the trailer with their company seals. Our loading sheet for our drivers will have a "Hot Topic" documented on the load sheet."Verify that all seals are the customers seals or do not leave the customer until thecustomer breaks the seals, inspects the washout caps of being on and tight and resealed."

column168: THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL IS A VISCOUS EPOXY RESIN SOLUTION CONTAINING 10-30% ACETONE, AND IS SHIPPED ABOVED AMBIENT TEMPERATURE. THE RESIN WAS LOADED INTO THE CTMV BELOW THE REQUIRED DELIVERY TEMPERATURE. OUR DRIVER STOPPED AT A SERVICE FACILITY AND THE CTMV WAS STEAM HEATED UNTIL THE RESIN WAS 170 DEGREE FAHRENHEIT, WHICH IS WITHIN THE ACCEPTABLE DELIVERY RANGE. ACETONE BOILS AT ABOUT 133 DEGREE FAHRENHEIT, CONSEQUENTLY, HEATING THE RESIN IN THE CLOSED CTMV PRESSURIZED THE CTMV. AT 170 DEGREE FAHRENHEIT, ACETONE'S VAPOR PRESSURE IS ABOUT 13.5 PSIG. THIS IS BELOW THE CTMV'S DESIGN PRESSURE, AND THERE WAS NO OBSERVED RELEASE. THE CTMV ARRIVED AT THE CONSIGNEE WAS ABOUT 150 DEGREE FAHRENHEIT. OUR DRIVER OPENED A VENT TO BLEED OFF PRESSURE AND WAS CONCERNED THAT IT TOOK MUCH LONGER THAN USUAL. OUR DRIVER CONTACTED HIS DISPATCH OFFICE AND THE CONSIGNEE'S RECEIVER CONSULTED THEIR LABORATORY FOR ADVICE. THEY ADVISED THEM TO CONTINUE WITH THE UNLOADING PROCESS. OUR DRIVER FINISHED BLEEDING OFF PRESSURE THEN OPENED THE DOME LID TO VENT THE TRAILER AND BEGAN PUMPING THE RESIN TO THE CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE TANK. SHORTLY THEREAFTER, THEY NOTICED RESIN BOILING OUT OF THE CTMV DOME OPENING. THE CONSIGNEE CLEANED UP THE RELEASED MATERIAL.  OUR EVENT NUMBER 35873. THIS REPORT IS DELAYED BECAUSE THERE WAS NO PACKAGE FAILURE AND THE RELEASE WAS FROM NORMAL VENTING (OPENING THE DOME LID WHEN PUMPING PRODUCT FROM THE CTMV TO AVOID VACUUM-INDUCED DAMAGE TO THE CTMV), WHICH WOULD NOT REQUIRE A REPORT. IT IS BEING REPORTED BECAUSE, AFTER DISCUSSIONS WITH PHMSA, THE CONSIGNEE DID NOT EXPECT THE RELEASE TO OCCUR AS EVIDENCED BY NOT PLACING SPILL CONTAINMENT AROUND THE CTMV. IT IS ALSO BEING REPORTED BECAUSE OF THE CLEAN UP EFFORT REPORTED BY THE CONSIGNEE.
column169: Opening a package containing a material above its initial boiling point will cause the material to suddenly boil (flash evaporation). However, it appears that the resin's viscosity delayed this process to the extent that ourdriver wasable to bleed off pressure and open the CTMV dome lid without immediate incident. Therefore, we suggest thatadditional training and improved Consignee operating procedures for handling viscous resins at temperatures abovethe solvent's boiling point can help prevent recurrence.

column168: ON JANUARY 10,2013, FREEMAN ENVIROMENTAL RESPONDED TO THE SITE. UPON ARRIVAL, FREEMAN PERSONNEL MET WITH ONSITE FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL WHO REPORTED THERE WAS NO RELEASE FROM THE ISO CONTAINER. THE IL STATE PATROL WOULD NOT AUTHORIZE REMOVAL OF THE ISO CONTAINER UNTIL THE MORNING OF JANUARY 11,2013. FREEMAN PERSONNEL REMAINED ON SITE TO MONITOR THE CONTAINER OVERNIGHT AND ON THE MORNING OF JANUARY 11,2013, FREEMAN PERSONNEL REPORTED THERE WAS A VISIBLE RELEASE OF RESIDUAL CHLORACETYL CHLORIDE PRODUCT LEAKING FROM ONE OF THE COLLECTION HOSES ON EITHER SIDE OF THE ISO CONATINER. MABAS REGIONAL HAZMAT TEAM CONFIRMED THERE WAS A RELEASE OF PRODUCT AND FREEMAN PERSONNEL REMAINED ONSITE TO MONITOR THE SITE OVERNIGHT. ON JANUARY 12,2013, REPRESENTATIVES OF TRIMAC, DOW CHEMICAL AND FREEMAN ENVIROMENTAL WERE ONSITE TO PERFORM A TRANSFER OF THE CONTAINER UTILIZING EQUIPMENT PROVIDED BY DOW CHEMICAL. DUE TO ANTICIPATED PRECIPITATION IN THE AREA AND THE POTENTIAL FOR A CHEMICAL REACTION, THE CONTAINER COULD NOT BE MOVED UNTIL CONDUCIVE WEATHER CONDITIONS WERE PRESENT. FREEMAN ENVIROMENTAL PLACED A TARP OVER THE CONTAINER AND REMAINED ONSITE TO MONITOR THE SITE. ON JANUARY 14, 2013, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE RESIDUAL CHLORACETYL CHLORIDE HAD REACTED WITH WATER AND FORMED MONOCHLOROACETIC ACID SOLUTION ON THE TARP, TANK AND SOIL. THE ALMA KINMUNDY FD DILUTED THE MATERIAL WITH MATERIAL WITH LARGE VOLUMES OF WATER AND THE CONTAINER WAS REMOVED FROM THE SITE. FREEMAN PERSONNEL REMAINED ONSITE OVERNIGHT TO MONITOR THE SITE. ON JANUARY 15,2013, FREEMAN PERSONNEL NEUTRALIZED THE IMPACTED SOILS AND APPLIED ABSORBENTS TO THE DIESEL FUEL IMPACTED AREA WHICH WAS FROZEN. ON JANUARY 16, 2013, THE IMPACTED SOIL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND EXCAVATED.

column168: Problem/Incident Statement While Loading Toluene into 3000 gallon compartment on Nexeo bulk tanker, compartment overflowed into containment cell under scale. column168: The Diesel Direct driver was driving downhill Defco Park Road when the truck began to slide on ice.  The GPS reports that the truck was going 6 MPH when it started to slide.  The truck eventually tipped over on it's side after teetering for a second or two.  The force of the truck landing on its side caused a rupture in a weld seam on the tank.  This rupture was in the rear passengers side of the tank and was approximately 5 feet in length by 4 inches wide.  As soon as the driver could get out of the truck he witnessed the diesel fuel pouring out of the rupture and could do nothing to stop the flow of the diesel fuel.  The driver immediately contacted 911 and his supervisor.  It did not take more than 5-8 minutes for all 2500 gallons of the diesel fuel to leave the tank.
column169: Diesel Direct has spoken to all drivers within the company about the dangers of driving in icy conditions, when a vehicle is sliding on ice you should not accelerate or brake, just try to steer clear of any obstacles.  This will be a topic in all safety meetings prior to and during winter conditions.  Our risk management insurance company, Energi, has been reviewing the different options for driving simulators with the intention of purchasing one or two and utilizing these simulators to train all of our drivers at least once a year.      Diesel Direct believes that if local towns/cities were given more money in their budgets they would be able to treat their roads better in the event of snow & ice conditions.  It does not appear that this road had been treated at all for ice.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While traveling, vehicle ws involved in an accident, which caused truck to overturn off side of roadway. Tanker was damaged, as a result of the accident, which resulted in the release of approximately 420 gallons of petroleum crude oil. Free product was released to the soils adjacent to rhe roadside. There were no waterways affected or threatened by the release. Local Responders assessed the site, secured the area, and evacuated immediate area, consisting of local residences. An elementary school nearby the incident was closed for the day, as a precautionary measure, due to the nature of the product and potential risks. Southland Response of Henderson, Texas was dispatched to perform the cleanup. Air was monitored and work zone was established. Absorbent material was applied to absorb free product within the roadside soils. Southland Response proceeded to recover spent absorbents, and excavated impacted soils. Confirmation samples were pulled, which were returned within acceptable limits, and site was restored to prexisting condition.  Approximately 52 tons of contaminated soils were generated during cleanup efforts, which were transported for disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations. There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Lessley Services will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: On January 22, 2013 at approximately 10:27am, a company driver had just completed loading his cargo tank at the Murphy Exploration and Production oil lease in Camp County, Texas. The load consisted of approximately 167 barrels of crude oil. While in route to the delivery point, the driver proceeded northbound on US Hwy 59 Business.  At the intersection of US Hwy 59 Business and US Hwy 59, the driver attempted to turn westbound onto US 59 toward the on-ramp. Due to an unsafe speed, the transport vehicle overturned onto its right side.  The transport came to rest lying partially on the roadway and the right shoulder of the roadway. No product was released from the cargo tank due to the crash. Emergency Services were summoned to the scene as well as company personnel. THe driver was taken to De Tar Hospital via Victoria EMS for evaluation.  The driver was later treated and released with only minor injuries.  Another company transport was brought to the scene to transfer the load.  After the transfer was complete, wrecker services uprighted the transport and towed it off site.  No further action was required.
column169: The root cause of this lay-over accident was due to an unsafe speed while making a turn. Contributing factors include load surge due to a partial load on a transport with high center of gravity. The vehicle's estimated speed just before the lay-over was 25 mph.      Additional awareness training on the factors that caused and contributed to this event is warranted. Drivers have particiated in an accident review process to include discussion on the hazards of unsafe speed, load surge, and high center of gravity.

column168: on 1/30/2013 at aprox 12:30pm we received a call that one of our vehicles was involved in an accident. Our transport vehicle identified as unit 309 had left the roadway on the left side, struck a guardrail and flipped over in the median. We immediately responded by contacting an environmental contractor and a towing contractor as well as an adjuster to meet us on scene. We immediately began communications with the State HP to relay our plans to remediate the accident scene. WE arrived on scene at approx 3:30pm. Haz Mat had control of the scene until we were able to remove the product from the tank. At that time, the truck was rolled back over and removed from the scene.  Under the circumstances of the accident, the situation was the best possible scenario. When the truck flipped over and slid to a stop, it pushed an earthen dam up in front of the tractor, which stopped any free product from flowing directly into the storm drain. The estimated rate of leakage was slow enough that the ground soaked up the product before it could flow into the storm drain. Both ends of the storm system were checked and no evidence of product was found.  Oil dry was applied to the roadway to soak any product up and avoid creating a hazard for traffic. An excavation of surgace contaminated soils was conducted on Monday Feb 4th. All contaminated soils were removed and all remaining product was removed from the roadway.

column168: On January 4, 2013, Union Pacific Railroad came to Agrium Advanced Technologies rail yard to conduct a routine switch of rail cars at about 10:00 a.m. During the switch, a rail car carrying Hazardous Waste Solid was "bumped" by the UP Railroad. This "bump" caused material to fall from the open-top gondola rail car to the ground. The spill was approximately 5-10 pounds. At about 16:15 on January 4 during routine Inspection of the rail area, the spill was discovered and promptly cleaned. The spill cleanup was complete by 17:00 on January 4. Report of the spill was made to the NRC by 17:35.
column169: Investigation of the spill was made and was found that the an employee had placed materials too high In the rail car causing material to the stacked higher than the top edge. Also, the gondola rail car cover was not present during the incident. Given the above, Agrium Advanced Technologies retrained all workers on proper loading techniques. AAT also changed equipment and operating procedures to allow for consistent use of the gondola rail car cover during Union Pacific Railroad switches.

column168: We load rail cars from trucks at this facility. The driver parked in the unloading area at the facility and proceeded to connect all of the compartments via hose to the suction header on the unloading pump at the facility. Another person prepared the rail car for loading. They opened the top dome to verify that it was empty. Then they took off the cap on the bottom loading valve on the rail car. The procedure then has them open the valve and close it again, leaving the cap off. The problem with this load was that the bottom valve on the rail car came in and it was open. When the person thought they were opening the valve, they actually closed it. Then when they thought they were closing it, they were actually opening it. At this point, the transfer pump was turned on and the filling of the rail car started. The person that was at the rail car noticed the red diesel flowing below and shut down the pump. He then closed the outlet valve. This pump operates at about 1000 gallons per minute and about 1300 gallons exited the car before the valve was closed. The released product made its way to the evaporation pond via an oil water separator. The oil water separator was not designed for this heavy of loading and passed the diesel directly to the pond. We had extreme rain conditions this particular evening and had concerns of the evaporation pond getting too full. We called in a vacuum truck to prevent the diesel from spreading further. None of the release left the property.
column169: The rail car loading procedure has been revised so that the bottom valve is physically checked by putting your and up the 4" opening to verify that the operation of the valve is closed before filling the rail car.

column168: ON JANUARY 4, 2013, A FLATBED TRANSPORT OPERATED BY NCH CORPORATION WAS TRAVELING THROUGH THE INTERSECTION OF COUNTY ROAD 50 AND COUNTY ROAD 9, WHEN A TRACTOR-TRAILER FAILED TO STOP AT THE STOP SIGN AND COLLIDED WITH THE UNIT. AS RESULT OF THE IMPACT, APPROXIMATELY 330 POUNDS OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE, 2,868.1 POUNDS OF PAA VIGOROX, AND 165 GALLONS OF METHANOL WERE RELEASED TO THE ASPHALT ROADWAY AND SOIL SURFACE ADJACENT TO THE ROADWAY.  A REPRESENTATIVE WITH NCH CORPORATION, MR. MIKE NEAR, RETAINED CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES, L.C. (CES), TO MANAGE THE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP OF THE SITE. BASED ON THE AVAILABLE INFORMATION THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER DISPATCHED A CREW WITH SPRINGER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (SES) TO ASSESS AND REMEDIATE THE SITE.  SES PERSONNEL ARRIVED AND ASSESSED THE SITE. CREWS DEPLOYED GRANULAR ABSORBENT TO THE ROADWAY TO SOLIDIFY THE FREE PRODUCT. WHILE THE TWO TRUCKS WERE BEING REMOVED FROM THE SITE, SES PERSONNEL BEGAN EXCAVATING AND STOCKPILING THE IMPACTED SOIL. ONCE THE TRUCKS WERE REMOVED, CREWS APPLIED ADDITIONAL ABSORBENT TO THE ROADWAY. SPENT ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS COLLECTED AND MOVED TO ONSITE STOCKPILE. WITH THE SITE CONTAINED, SES PERSONNEL DEMOBILIZED AND SCHEDULED TO RETURN THE FOLLOWING DAY.  ON JANUARY 2, 2013, SES PERSONNEL MET ONSITE WITH TCEQ PERSONNEL TO DISCUSS THE REMEDIATION ACTIVITIES. THE TCEQ REPRESENTATIVE REVIEWED THE MSDS SHEETS AND ADVISED THAT THE STOCKPILED MATERIAL COULD BE BLENDED BACK INTO LOCATION PENDING PH ANALYSIS. AFTER MEETING WITH THE TCEQ REPRESENTATIVES, SES CREWS CONTINUED EXCAVATION OPERATIONS. ALL EXCAVATED MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN THE ONSITE STOCKPILE. CREWS COLLECTED TEO COMPOSITE SAMPLES FROM THE STOCKPILE FOR PH ANALYSIS. SES PERSONNEL DEMOBILIZED FROM THE SITE.  COMPOSITE SOIL SAMPLES RETURNED WITH PH LEVELS WITHIN ACCEPTABLE LEVELS. ON JANUARY 17, 2013, SES PERSONNEL RETURNED TO THE SITE AND BLENDED THE STOCKPILED MATERIAL BACK INTO LOCATION. ONCE NO ADDITIONAL CORRECTIVE ACTION WERE NECESSARY, THE CREW FROM SES DEMOBILIZED FROM THE SITE.  EXCAVATED MATERIAL WAS BLENDED BACK INTO LOCATION. THEREFORE, NO DISPOSAL WAS NECESSARY FOR THIS PROJECT.
column169: NO COMMENT PROVIDED.

BASED ON THE AVAILABLE INFORMATION THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER DISPATCHED A CREW WITH SPRINGER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (SES) TO ASSESS AND REMEDIATE THE SITE.  SES PERSONNEL ARRIVED AND ASSESSED THE SITE. CREWS DEPLOYED GRANULAR ABSORBENT TO THE ROADWAY TO SOLIDIFY THE FREE PRODUCT. WHILE THE TWO TRUCKS WERE BEING REMOVED FROM THE SITE, SES PERSONNEL BEGAN EXCAVATING AND STOCKPILING THE IMPACTED SOIL. ONCE THE TRUCKS WERE REMOVED, CREWS APPLIED ADDITIONAL ABSORBENT TO THE ROADWAY. SPENT ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS COLLECTED AND MOVED TO ONSITE STOCKPILE. WITH THE SITE CONTAINED, SES PERSONNEL DEMOBILIZED AND SCHEDULED TO RETURN THE FOLLOWING DAY.  ON JANUARY 2, 2013, SES PERSONNEL MET ONSITE WITH TCEQ PERSONNEL TO DISCUSS THE REMEDIATION ACTIVITIES. THE TCEQ REPRESENTATIVE REVIEWED THE MSDS SHEETS AND ADVISED THAT THE STOCKPILED MATERIAL COULD BE BLENDED BACK INTO LOCATION PENDING PH ANALYSIS. AFTER MEETING WITH THE TCEQ REPRESENTATIVES, SES CREWS CONTINUED EXCAVATION OPERATIONS. ALL EXCAVATED MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN THE ONSITE STOCKPILE. CREWS COLLECTED TEO COMPOSITE SAMPLES FROM THE STOCKPILE FOR PH ANALYSIS. SES PERSONNEL DEMOBILIZED FROM THE SITE.  COMPOSITE SOIL SAMPLES RETURNED WITH PH LEVELS WITHIN ACCEPTABLE LEVELS. ON JANUARY 17, 2013, SES PERSONNEL RETURNED TO THE SITE AND BLENDED THE STOCKPILED MATERIAL BACK INTO LOCATION. ONCE NO ADDITIONAL CORRECTIVE ACTION WERE NECESSARY, THE CREW FROM SES DEMOBILIZED FROM THE SITE.  EXCAVATED MATERIAL WAS BLENDED BACK INTO LOCATION. THEREFORE, NO DISPOSAL WAS NECESSARY FOR THIS PROJECT.
