column62: Human Error; Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Overfilled
column168: HOME HEATING FUEL DRIVER AND TRUCK DISPATCHED TO CUSTOMER’S HOME TO FILL EMPTY HOME HEATING FUEL TANK. THE TANK IS LOCATED IN THE CUSTOMER'S BASEMENT, INACCESSIBLE TO THE DRIVER. FILL SPOUT PROTRUDES THROUGH THE EXTERIOR WALL OF THE HOUSE. TANK IS FITTED WITH WHISTLE VENT. SOME TIME PRIOR TO THE DRIVER'S ARRIVAL, CUSTOMER HAD REMOVED A 2" FITTING FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK AND DID NOT REPLACE IT. CUSTOMER WAS NOT AT HOME DURING DELIVERY. DRIVER HOOKED UP HOSE AND BEGAN DELIVERY. WHISTLE VENT ON HEATING FUEL TANK DID NOT OPERATE OWING TO THE OPEN 2" FITTING WHICH DID NOT ALLOW PRESSURE TO BUILD UP DURING FILLING. DRIVER NOTICED FUEL SMELL AND DIESEL EXITING THE BASEMENT. DRIVER SECURED PUMPING, METER READING WAS 447GALS. DRIVER DEPLOYED SORBENT MATERIALS AND CALLED THE OFFICE FOR ASSISTANCE, WHICH ARRIVED ON SITE APPROXIMATELY 15 MINUTES LATER WITH MORE RESPONSE MATERIAL. OSRO CONTACTED AND RESPONDED WITH PERSONNEL AND AORBENT BOOM. APPROXIMATELY 49 GALLONS OF DIESEL WENT INTO A CULVERT DRAIN AND ENTERED A SMALL, CONSTRICTED COVE ON TONGASS NARROWS AND WAS COLLECTED THERE USING SORBENT BOOM AND MATERIAL. TANK HOLDS 275 GALS. TOTAL ESTIMATED RELEASE WAS 172GALS, MOST OF WHICH WENT INTO THE SOIL OF THE CUSTOMER'S BASEMENT UNDER FLOOR BOARDS AND SOIL WAS REMOVED/REPLACED BY CUSTOMER UNDER ALASKA DEPT OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION SUPERVISION AND DIRECTION.
column169: TRAINING AND OPERATING PROCEDURES ARE IN PLACE FOR THESE TYPES OF DELIVERIES. DELIVERIES OF THIS NATURE ARE NOT TO OCCUR IF PREVENTION DEVICES ARE NOT IN PLACE AND OPERATING CORRECTLY. DRIVER SHOULD HAVE STOPPED DELIVERY WHEN NO WHISTLE VENT WAS HEARD. REMEDIAL TRAINING AND REINFORCEMENT OF PROCEDURES WERE GIVEN TO DRIVER.

column168: V1 WAS EN-ROUTE TO MAKE A DELIVERY OF DIESEL FUEL TO PILOT TRAVEL CENTERS STORE #538 IN OAKDALE, WI WHEN HE REALIZED HIS TRAILER HAD DEVELOPED A LEAK. V1 STATED THAT ANOTHER MOTORIST INFORMED HIM OF THE LEAK, AFTER WHICH V1 TOOK IMMEDIATE ACTION TO GET OFF THE ROADWAY AND INTO A NEARBY PARKING LOT.    V1 IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED OUR CORPORATE OFFICE TO INFORM US OF THE LEAK. WE THEN DISPATCHED A CLEANUP CREW TO THE SCENE, TO CLEAN UP ANY SPILLED PRODUCT.    UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT WATER HAD FROZEN IN ONE OF THE DRAINS THAT COMES OFF THE BACK OF THE TRAILER. AS THE ICE EXPANDED IN THE DRAIN, IT CAUSED A CRACK IN THE SHELL OF THE TRAILER, DUE TO THE PRESSURE AND FRIGID TEMPERATURES. THE CRACK IN THE SHELL THEN CAUSED PRODUCT TO LEAK OUT OF THE TRAILER.
column169: GIVEN THE OBSCURE NATURE OF THE INCIDENT, THERE IS NOT A CLEAR ANSWER OF WHAT COULD HAVE BEEN DONE TO PREVENT SUCH A SCENARIO. HOWEVER, WE WILL CONTINUE TO EMPHASIZE THE IMPORTANCE OF PERFORMING THOROUGH PRE-TRIP AND POST-TRIP EQUIPMENT INSPECTION WITH ALL OF OUR DRIVERS, IN HOPES OF MITIGATING THE POSSIBILITY THAT ANOTHER SUCH SITUATION WOULD ARISE IN THE FUTURE.

column168: DRIVER LOADED DIESEL FUEL ON LANE #2; AT THE END OF THE LOAD, THE LOADING SYSTEM FAILED TO SHUT DOWN, OVERFILLING THE COMPARTMENT AND SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 200 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL IN LANE #2; ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN THE LOADING RACK AREA   DRIVER HIT THE EMERGENCY SHUTDOWN BUTTON AT THE RACK AND STOPPED THE FLOW OF PRODUCT; TERMINAL OPERATORS AND DRIVERS USED ABSORBENT PADS TO START SOAKING UP THE SPILLED DIESEL FUEL; CLEAN HARBORS WAS CALLED AND THEY CAME IN AND CLEANED UP THE BALANCE OF THE SPILL WITH A VAC TRUCK AND ADDITIONAL ABSORBENT PADS

column168: WE WERE NOT ABLE TO DETERMINE FOR CERTAIN THE EXACT CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT BUT HAVE THEORIZED THAT A UNIVERSAL JOINT IN THE SHORT DRIVELINE BETWEEN THE DIFFERENTIALS FAILED CAUSING THE DRIVELINE TO WHIP AROUND AND TEAR LOOSE THE FUEL PIPING UNDERNEATH THE CARGO TANK. THIS IN TURN CAUSED A FUEL LEAK WHICH WAS IGNITED BY THE SPARKING FROM THE BROKEN DRIVELINE.    BECAUSE OF THE REMOTE LOCATION OF THE TRUCK AND THE ADVANCED CONDITION OF THE FIRE, BY THE TIME THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED, THEY DETERMINED THAT THE BEST COURSE OF ACTION WAS TO ALLOW THE FIRE TO BURN ITSELF OUT, MOSTLY CONSUMING THE TRUCK AND THE CARGO.
column169: WE HAVE IMPLEMENTED MORE RIGOROUS INSPECTION STANDARDS AND ADDED DRIVER INCENTIVES TO HELP REDUCE THE POSSIBILITIES OF MECHANICAL FAILURES.
